### File Descriptions
```
- app.py
  The main Flask application file containing all backend routes, logic for reading/writing data files, version control, content scheduling, analytics, and rendering templates. Since the system is not highly complex, consolidating backend logic here simplifies maintenance.

- requirements.txt
  Lists Python dependencies, primarily Flask and any other required libraries.

- README.md
  Project overview, setup instructions, and usage notes.

- data/
  Directory containing all persistent data files in text format as specified:
  - users.txt: User information.
  - articles.txt: Article metadata and status.
  - article_versions.txt: Version history of articles.
  - approvals.txt: Approval workflow data.
  - workflow_stages.txt: Workflow configuration.
  - comments.txt: Editorial comments on article versions.
  - analytics.txt: Article engagement metrics.

- templates/
  HTML templates for each page as per specification:
  - dashboard.html: Main landing page with overview and navigation.
  - create_article.html: Article creation editor.
  - edit_article.html: Article editing with version tracking.
  - version_history.html: Viewing and restoring article versions.
  - my_articles.html: Userâ€™s article list with filters.
  - published_articles.html: Public content library.
  - content_calendar.html: Scheduled publication timeline.
  - article_analytics.html: Engagement metrics display.

- static/
  Static assets served by Flask:
  - css/styles.css: Stylesheet for consistent UI styling.
  - js/scripts.js: JavaScript for client-side interactivity.
  - img/: Folder for featured images and other media assets.
```
This structure supports modular development, easy testing starting from the Dashboard page, and clear separation of concerns between backend logic, templates, data storage, and static assets."

